# Introduction\
\
##function and importance of leaf traits \
-leaf traits allow us to measure the function of many processes within plants, including water/nutrient uptake, photosynthesis, and respiration\
-using these measurements allows us to examine what factors limit plant function and thus form selective pressure to structure plant communities\
-SLA, LDMC, thickness (explain functional significance of each) - relation to abiotic/environmental variables\
-understanding the significance of functional traits allows ecology to be a more accurately predictive science, which is important especially in a climate change perspective\
\
##Spatial\
-analyzing spatial patterns of functional variation allow us to describe what role local and community forces play in shaping plant communities\
-two hypotheses for how plant communities are shaped at a local level:\
	1) plasticity\
	2) species turnover\
-more variation at one site indicates that plasticity of functional traits is high and that trait plasticity more influentially structures plant communities\
-more variation between sites indicates that plasticity is low and that species turnover more influentially structures plant communities\
\
